where the context-dependent weighting CðDðinÞÞ is implemented as a Gaussian tuning function (Fig 2A, middle panel). Modules with preferred directions closest to the current context thus receive the highest weighting.
Errors in the model (right panel of Fig 2A) result from the discrepancy between the motor output (green vector) and the forces associated with the dynamics of the object (blue vector). Because both the motor output and the object dynamics are represented in a two-dimensional task space, the error on a given trial is also a two-dimensional vector (magenta vector). The magnitude (e(n)) and direction (yðenÞ) of the error vector both contribute to adaptation in the model.
The adaptive state for the ith module changes based on two processes (Fig 2B):

xðnþ1Þ i

